results.abstract: Astronauts Scott E Parazynski and Col Douglas H Wheelock will take part in risky spacewalk in effort to mend torn solar array on International Space Station (M)

headline.main: Risky Spacewalk Today to Mend Solar Array

results.snippet: In the procedure an astronaut will be out on the end of a 50-foot-long boom gripped by the space station’s robotic arm, either unsnagging or cutting a wire.
results.lead_paragraph: Astronauts will take part in an unusually risky spacewalk today in an effort to mend a torn solar array on the International Space Station. In the procedure, Scott E. Parazynski will be far out on a limb -- or, rather, out on the end of a 50-foot-long boom gripped by the space station's robotic arm. Dr. Parazynski will either unsnag or cut a wire that appears to have hung up on a hinge of a solar panel, putting two tears in a left-side solar array.

results.abstract: Astronaut Dr Scott E Parazynski repairs solar array on International Space Station that was damaged while being deployed; loss of array would have reduced station's ability to produce power and possibly have constrained future construction; photo (M)

headline.main: Astronaut Fixes Damage To Solar Array on Station

results.snippet: The repair to a solar array on the International Space Station was very delicate because of mechanical issues.
results.lead_paragraph: An astronaut on a daring spacewalk yesterday repaired a damaged solar array on the International Space Station. Dr. Scott E. Parazynski, a former emergency room physician, mended wounds on the wing, which developed two tears while being deployed Tuesday.

results.abstract: Editorial lauds recent space mission as testimonial to ingenuity of NASA, but also warns how precarious nation's space ventures can be when unexpected glitches develop; describes how primary mission--enlarging international space station and moving solar arrays--became more complex; says spacewalk to effect repairs was impressive
results.snippet: Under difficult conditions on an unusually busy and lengthy mission, NASA’s astronauts accomplished their tasks impressively.
results.lead_paragraph: The astronauts and their support team on the ground performed admirably under difficult conditions on an unusually busy and lengthy mission that ended with a smooth landing yesterday. Their accomplishments were a testimonial to the ingenuity of NASA -- and a warning of how precarious the nation's space ventures can become when unexpected glitches develop far from the nearest repair shop. The 15-day mission to enlarge the international space station now circling overhead was scheduled to be arduous from the start. The prime tasks were to add a new closet-size ''room'' that will allow new laboratories to be attached on future flights and to move large solar arrays that provide power to the station. Those two tasks alone constituted the most challenging construction job ever undertaken in space.

results.abstract: One view of "doing right" for the future.

headline.main: Facing Looming Threats, From Space or From Us

results.snippet: One view of "doing right" for the future.
results.lead_paragraph: After I wrote my post examining what makes it worthwhile for a current generation to work to limit future risks, I sent an e-mail to a few contacts exploring risks and responses, inviting them to weigh in. A note came back from the Apollo 9 astronaut Rusty Schweickart, who has lately been pressing for the United States to intensify efforts to limit a danger both far more concretely understood than global warming and far less in vogue as a serious threat -- the reality that a very large rock will inevitably head on a collision course for Earth.

results.lead_paragraph: Tagging along with Mike Huckabee over the course of two days last week as he stumped through eastern Iowa, an observation came to mind time and again about how much he still remained a small-town Baptist pastor.

headline.main: Work on International Space Station Continues

results.snippet: The crew of the International Space Station are performing a nonstop series of tasks inside and outside the station.
results.lead_paragraph: Even as the shuttle Discovery touched down at the Kennedy Space Center last week, the shuttle Atlantis was being readied for a mission to take up another new module to the International Space Station as early as Dec. 6. Whether the launching will happen on time depends largely on what the station's commander, Peggy Whitson, the Russian cosmonaut Yuri Malenchenko and the American astronaut Daniel M. Tani get done in a nonstop series of tasks inside and outside the station.

results.abstract: Henry Louis Gates Jr Op-Ed article holds that persistent poverty among black families must be addressed before it becomes permanent; says his research shows astonishing pattern that many successful African-Americans descended from former slaves who managed to obtain property by 1920; asserts that bold and innovative approach to problem of black poverty would be to look at ways to turn tenants into homeowners; says property owners feel sense of ownership in their future and their society; drawing (M)

headline.main: Forty Acres and a Gap in Wealth

results.snippet: We can’t afford to wait any longer to address the causes of persistent poverty among most black families.
results.lead_paragraph: LAST week, the Pew Research Center published the astonishing finding that 37 percent of African-Americans polled felt that ''blacks today can no longer be thought of as a single race'' because of a widening class divide. From Frederick Douglass to the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., perhaps the most fundamental assumption in the history of the black community has been that Americans of African descent, the descendants of the slaves, either because of shared culture or shared oppression, constitute ''a mighty race,'' as Marcus Garvey often put it.

results.abstract: Roberta Smith Art Review column on 'Rabbit,' metalic balloon by artist Jeff Koons that made its debut in Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade; balloon is more sculpture-like than traditional brightly colored balloons; photo (S)

headline.main: An Artist's Bunny Balloon Sheds Its Steel Skin

results.snippet: Jeff Koons’s floating silver “Rabbit” was distinctive, but not out of place amid the more familiar brand-name balloons in Macy’s Thanksgiving Day Parade.
results.lead_paragraph: Drifting above Broadway yesterday during one of the sunnier Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parades in recent memory, Jeff Koons's big silver ''Rabbit'' balloon sort of looked like art. Not too much, but enough to make a difference. First of all, there was its metallic monochrome color, whereas most of its inflatable fellow travelers were medleys of bright colors and signature details. The truck-size version of Shrek, for example, just ahead of the Koons, had green skin, brown-and-red plaid pants and a goofy grin.

results.abstract: Matt DeBergalis and Ben Rahn have raised $32 million in small donations for Democratic candidates since they started Web site ActBlue.com in 2004; two say they are gearing up to make good on promise that site will raise $100 million for Democrats in this election cycle; chart; photo (M)
results.snippet: Two youthful computer whizzes are quietly trying to change how campaigns raise money, netting millions of dollars for Democrats in the process.
results.lead_paragraph: They may not inhabit the traditional world of high-dollar campaign fund-raising, but two youthful computer whizzes are quietly and behind the scenes trying to change how campaigns raise money, netting millions of dollars for Democrats in the process. Operating from an office just off Harvard Square, Matt DeBergalis and Ben Rahn, through the Web site they created, ActBlue.com, have raised $32 million since it was started in 2004. They are gearing up to make good on their promise that it will raise $100 million for Democrats in this election cycle.
